  5. Credential Stuffing
  Definition

  Credential Stuffing uses stolen usernames and passwords from one data breach to access accounts on other websites.

  Example

  Suppose a shopping website suffers a data breach.

  Leaked password:

  Soham@123

  The attacker now tries the same credentials on:

  Gmail
  GitHub
  Instagram
  Amazon

  If the user reused the password, multiple accounts are compromised.

  Why Credential Stuffing Works

  Many people reuse the same password across different services.

  Defense
  Unique password for every website
  Password Manager
  MFA
  6. Phishing
  Definition

  Phishing is a social engineering attack where attackers trick users into revealing sensitive information such as passwords, OTPs, or banking details.

  Example

  Victim receives an email:

  URGENT!

  Your Bank Account Has Been Locked.

  Click Here Immediately.

  The link opens a fake banking website.

  The victim enters:

  Username
  Password
  OTP

  The attacker steals everything.

  Common Signs of Phishing
  Urgent language
  Unknown sender
  Spelling mistakes
  Suspicious URLs
  Requests for passwords or OTPs
  Defense
  Verify the sender
  Check URLs carefully
  Never share OTPs
  Enable MFA
  7. Social Engineering
  Definition

  Social Engineering is the practice of manipulating people into performing actions that compromise security.

  Unlike technical attacks, it targets human behavior rather than software vulnerabilities.

  Why It Is Dangerous

  Humans are often easier to deceive than computers.

  Even highly secure systems can be compromised if users voluntarily reveal their credentials.

  Common Types of Social Engineering
  A. Phishing

  Uses emails or fake websites.

  B. Vishing

  Voice phishing.

  Example: "Hello. This is Microsoft Support. Please tell me your OTP."
  C. Smishing

  SMS phishing.

  Example:

  Your Bank Account Has Been Locked.

  Click Here.
  D. Baiting

  The attacker leaves:

  Salary_List_2026.pdf.exe

  or

  an infected USB drive.

  The victim opens it.

  Malware installs automatically.

  E. Tailgating

  An attacker follows an employee into a restricted building without authorization.

  Phishing vs Social Engineering
  Phishing	Social Engineering
  Specific attack	Broader category
  Usually email/websites	Targets human psychology
  One type of social engineering	Includes phishing, vishing, smishing, baiting, tailgating
  8. Password Policies

  Organizations define password policies to improve security.

  Typical rules include:

  Minimum length of 12–16 characters
  Uppercase letters
  Lowercase letters
  Numbers
  Special characters
  No common passwords
  No password reuse
